1 Exercise

We currently have \(3\) ways of generating Gaussian samples in R:

  • the native rnorm() using the inverse transform
  • Box-Muller transform
  • rejection sampling (see lecture notes for code)

For \(50\) simulation runs, and for all three methods:

  • generate 10^5 samples using

  • time the generation process using Sys.time()

  • calculate the KS statistic (the one-sample Kolmogorov-Smirnov statistic) to check quality of the sample, e.g.

    • X <- rnorm(10ˆ5)
    • F_hat <- ecdf(X)
    • F_hat_eval <- F_hat(sort(X))
    • F_eval <- pnorm(sort(X))
    • KS_stats <- max(abs(F_hat_eval - F_eval))

Compare the three methods using your simulation results.

Figure 1.1: In this plot we compare the times the different sampling methods used to generate 10^5 of Random variables according to a standard Gaussian distribution

We see that the Rejection sampling takes way more time than the Inverse and the Box-Muller Sampling Method. It seems that the inverse is slightly faster than the Box-Muller sampling.

Figure 1.2: In this plot we compare the Kolmogorov-Smirnov statistics during the simulation study emerging from the different sampling methods

We see that none of thge Kolmogorov-Smirnov statistics is consistently higher or smaller than the the other ones. We conclude that, the sampling is equally “good”.
